<p dir="auto">The lines starting with an “@” symbol contains the header information.
The @SQ tag is the reference sequence dictionary; SN refers to the
reference sequence name and LN refers to the reference sequence length.
If you don’t see lines starting with the “@” symbol, the header
information is probably missing. You can generate this information again
by running the command below, where <code>ref.fa</code> is the reference FASTA file
used to map the reads.</p>
<div class="highlight highlight-source-shell notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" dir="auto" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content="samtools view -bT sequence/ref.fa aln.sam &gt; aln.bam"><pre>samtools view -bT sequence/ref.fa aln.sam <span class="pl-k">&gt;</span> aln.bam</pre></div>
<p dir="auto">If the header information is available, we can convert a SAM file into
BAM by using <code>samtools view -b</code>. In newer versions of SAMtools, the
input format is auto-detected, so we no longer need the <code>-S</code> parameter.</p>
<div class="highlight highlight-source-shell notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" dir="auto" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content="samtools view -b eg/ERR188273_chrX.sam &gt; eg/my.bam"><pre>samtools view -b eg/ERR188273_chrX.sam <span class="pl-k">&gt;</span> eg/my.bam</pre></div>
<div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h2 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">Converting a BAM file to a CRAM file</h2><a id="user-content-converting-a-bam-file-to-a-cram-file" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: Converting a BAM file to a CRAM file" href="#converting-a-bam-file-to-a-cram-file"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div>
<p dir="auto">The CRAM format is even more compact. Use <code>samtools view</code> with the <code>-T</code>
and <code>-C</code> arguments to convert a BAM file into CRAM.</p>
<div class="highlight highlight-source-shell notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" dir="auto" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content="samtools view -T genome/chrX.fa -C -o eg/ERR188273_chrX.cram eg/ERR188273_chrX.bam

ls -lh eg/ERR188273_chrX.[sbcr]*am"><pre>samtools view -T genome/chrX.fa -C -o eg/ERR188273_chrX.cram eg/ERR188273_chrX.bam

ls -lh eg/ERR188273_chrX.[sbcr]<span class="pl-k">*</span>am</pre></div>
